      "message": "\u003e \u003e This is making it pretty complicated if we split responsibility across dbus interfaces. What I was expecting was\n\u003e /xyz/openbmc_project/software/bmc\n\u003e Hosts update and version interfaces for the bmc\n\u003e \u003e /xyz/openbmc_project/software/\u003cswId\u003e\n\u003e hosts update and version interfaces for other components. \n\u003e \n\u003e Why we have to treat BMC as a special case and use a fixed path for it and use \u003cswId\u003e for all others?\n\nThe actual requirement is that for non-multipart updates, we need to be able to target an update at \"this\" bmc.  Having a known path for that seemed like the easiest, and it\u0027s what we did in the past, but if there\u0027s a simpler way, great.\n\n\u003e \n\u003e Moreover, there can be more than one version for the BMC, for example, active, activating, staged so i don\u0027t think we can put all of them at the same DBus path. \n\nI would expect active to go in the bmc path, because that\u0027s what the bmc is running NOW.  The others are other inventory items, that yes, I would agree should go in other objects.\n\n\n\u003e As per design, the idea was to keep Version and Update interfaces at same path /xyz/openbmc_project/software/\u003cswId\u003e. While doing proto-typing i felt that duplicating the Update interface doesn\u0027t make sense since nothing is changing for that interface from one BMC version to another, its just a way to deliver the update command to the component. So i kept it separate from the Version interface but used an association to link the Version and Update interfaces. I was going to float those design changes for discussion but its good we are discussing now.\n\n\nI personally think that design change makes code complicated;  We\u0027re accessing two objects instead of one, and having to map an association between two things that are effectively the same thing.\n\nI wouldn\u0027t really expect that the \"staging\" path have an update interface.  You\u0027re updating the active version, not updating the \"staged\" version (at least for Redfish).  Or if you are updating the staged version, that\u0027s a different operation.\n\n\u003e \n\u003e \n\u003e \u003e Once of these components might also be a \"copy\" of the bmc.\n\u003e \n\u003e I am not sure what you mean by copy of bmc?\n\n\n/xyz/openbmc_project/software/ABC\n\nMight represent an identical object as\n\n/xyz/openbmc_project/software/bmc\n\nIf you need the ABC name for some internal accounting.\n\n\u003e \n\u003e \n\u003e \u003e \u003e /xyz/openbmc_project/software/update/bmc for hosting the update interface?\n\u003e \u003e \n\u003e \u003e I\u0027m not sure what this would accomplish, aside from putting it at a different namespace path.  The complexity is that the code has split up the dbus object paths for things that represent the same thing. \n\u003e \n\u003e Version interface is representing the particular version of a component software and there can be n version interfaces for that component depending upon what state (running, staged, activating etc) that version is in. Contrary, Update interface provides a way to trigger/deliver an update action to a component daemon, which shouldn\u0027t change from one version to another.\n\nSee above about the \"active\" version being special, and should exist on the same object.  At the end of the day, think of it like a device.  We have a physical bmc, it has software on it, as well as an interface to update.  That\u0027s physically \"one\" path.\n\n\u003e \n\u003e \u003e We can have multiple interfaces on the same dbus path, and that\u0027s generally how we represent \"this object can do multiple things\". We fall back to associations when we\u0027re operating in different path namespaces, relating two distinct objects to one another, but by in large we will have the same path host multiple interfaces if that path just has multiple capabilities.\n\u003e \n\u003e I agree that we could have kept both Update and Version as one object but I have explained above the reasoning for keeping them separate. Please let me know if it makes sense?",
